      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">4</infon>
        <offset>496</offset>
        <text>Infected algal cultures of Phaeocystis globosa grown in coastal North Sea water contained gamma- and alphaproteobacterial phylotypes that were distinct from those in the non-infected control cultures 5 h after infection.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">5</infon>
        <offset>717</offset>
        <text>The gammaproteobacterial population at this time mainly consisted of Alteromonas sp.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">6</infon>
        <offset>802</offset>
        <text>cells that were attached to the infected but still intact host cells.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">7</infon>
        <offset>872</offset>
        <text>Nano-scale secondary-ion mass spectrometry (nanoSIMS) showed ~20% transfer of organic matter derived from the infected 13C- and 15N-labelled P. globosa cells to Alteromonas sp.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">8</infon>
        <offset>1049</offset>
        <text>cells.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">9</infon>
        <offset>1056</offset>
        <text>Subsequent, viral lysis of P. globosa resulted in the formation of aggregates that were densely colonised by bacteria.
</text>
        <annotation id="T5">
          <infon key="type">Increase</infon>
          <infon key="brat-type">text-bound</infon>
